An Evolutionary Study of Innovation, Competition, and Convergence in Economics

Sun Tanomkiattikun

Johns Hopkins University

December 4, 2023

Introduction

Nelson & Winter's Evolutionary Model

  • Heterogeneous routines of imitation and innovation

  • Dynamics of competition

Dosi et al.'s Endogenous Growth Model

  • multi-country, multi-industry agent-based model

  • convergence

  • homogeneous and fixed routines

The Model

1. Firms' revenue -> Reinvest in R&D

2. Total factor productivity may increase.

3. Lower cost -> Competitive pricing -> Gain market share.

4. Unprofitable firms exit the market. New firms enter.

5. Repeat until dynamic equilibrium.

Results - Overview

Setup

  • 1 Industry
  • 10 Countries
  • 20 Firms per country
  • Lowest profitable 50% of all firms exit the industry each cycle.

4 Settings

Setting Innovation Imitation Market Structure $\beta$-Convergence
1 High High Monopolistically Competitive Yes
2 High Low Oligopoly / Monopoly No
3 Low High Monopolistically Competitive Yes
4 Low Low Monopolistically Competitive Yes

Results - Firms' Routines and Economic Growth

Setting 1: Both Innovation and Imitation are Effective

Average productivity evolves together

Equally likely to innovate or imitate

Results - Firms' Routines and Economic Growth

Setting 2: Effective Innovation

Oligopoly / Monopoly

Results - Firms' Routines and Economic Growth

Setting 3: Effective Imitation

Strong signs of convergence

High density of imitators

Results - Firms' Routines and Economic Growth

Setting 4: Both Innovation and Imitation are Ineffective

Strong signs of convergence but low growth

Firms still invest in R&D despite its ineffectiveness

Results - Market Concentration

Setting 1: Both Innovation and Imitation are Effective

Highly competitive (low concentration), Gradually increasing HHI

Results - Market Concentration

Setting 2: Effective Innovation

Few companies dominate the market

Results - Market Concentration

Setting 3: Effective Imitation

Close to Perfect Competition

Results - Market Concentration

Setting 4: Both Innovation and Imitation are Ineffective

Mostly competitive, Upper bound becomes monopoly

Results - $\beta$-Convergence

Setting 1: Both Innovation and Imitation are Effective

Significant convergence while variation is high

Results - $\beta$-Convergence

Setting 2: Effective Innovation

Divergence toward Oligopoly / Monopoly

Results - $\beta$-Convergence

Setting 3: Effective Imitation

Strong and persistent convergence

Results - $\beta$-Convergence

Setting 4: Both Innovation and Imitation are Ineffective

Weak but persistent convergence

Conclusion

  • Firms' decisions are heterogeneous

  • Routines depend on R&D effectiveness

  • Equilibrium is path-dependent

  • Convergence is strongest with effective imitation

Future Research

  • More expansive model (e.g. labor market, financial market)

  • Different imitation and innovation processes

  • Interconnectedness of international markets

  • Simulation with historical data
